                        <th> </th><th>82</th><td class="r"><span>Alias /trac/chrome/site /path/to/projectenv/htdocs</span> </td>
                      </tr><tr>
                        <th> </th><th>83</th><td class="r"><span>&lt;Directory "/path/to/projectenv/htdocs"&gt;</span> </td>
                      </tr><tr>
                        <th> </th><th>84</th><td class="r"><span>&nbsp; Order allow,deny</span> </td>
                      </tr><tr>
                        <th> </th><th>85</th><td class="r"><span>&nbsp; Allow from all</span> </td>
                      </tr><tr>
                        <th> </th><th>86</th><td class="r"><span>&lt;/Directory&gt;</span> </td>
                      </tr><tr>
                        <th> </th><th>87</th><td class="r"><span>}}}</span> </td>
                      </tr><tr>
                        <th> </th><th>88</th><td class="r"><span></span> </td>
                      </tr><tr class="last">
                        <th> </th><th>89</th><td class="r"><span>Alternatively to hacking `/trac/chrome/site`, you can directly specify path to static resources using `htdocs_location` configuration option in [wiki:TracIni trac.ini]:</span> </td>
                      </tr>
            </tbody><tbody class="unmod">
                  <tr>
                          <th>63</th><th>90</th><td class="l"><span>{{{</span> </td>
                  </tr><tr>
                          <th>64</th><th>91</th><td class="l"><span>[trac]</span> </td>
                  </tr>
            </tbody><tbody class="mod">
                      <tr class="first">
                        <th>65</th><th> </th><td class="l"><span>htdocs_location = <del></del>/trac-htdocs</span> </td>
                      </tr>
                      <tr class="last">
                        <th> </th><th>92</th><td class="r"><span>htdocs_location = <ins>http://yourhost.example.org</ins>/trac-htdocs</span> </td>
                      </tr>
            </tbody><tbody class="unmod">
                  <tr>
                          <th>66</th><th>93</th><td class="l"><span>}}}</span> </td>
                  </tr><tr>
                          <th>67</th><th>94</th><td class="l"><span></span> </td>
                  </tr><tr>
                          <th>68</th><th>95</th><td class="l"><span>Trac will then use this URL when embedding static resources into HTML pages. Of course, you still need to make the Trac `htdocs` directory available through the web server at the specified URL, for example by copying (or linking) the directory into the document root of the web server:</span> </td>
                  </tr><tr>
                          <th>69</th><th>96</th><td class="l"><span>{{{</span> </td>
                  </tr>
            </tbody><tbody class="mod">
                      <tr class="first">
                        <th>70</th><th> </th><td class="l"><span>$ ln -s /<del>usr/share/trac/htdocs /var/www/your_site.com/htdocs</del>/trac-htdocs</span> </td>
                      </tr>
                      <tr class="last">
                        <th> </th><th>97</th><td class="r"><span>$ ln -s /<ins>path/to/www/trac/htdocs /var/www/yourhost.example.org</ins>/trac-htdocs</span> </td>
                      </tr>
            </tbody><tbody class="unmod">
                  <tr>
                          <th>71</th><th>98</th><td class="l"><span>}}}</span> </td>
                  </tr>
            </tbody><tbody class="add">
                  <tr class="first">
                          <th> </th><th>99</th><td class="r"><ins></ins> </td>
                  </tr><tr>
                          <th> </th><th>100</th><td class="r"><ins>Note that in order to get this `htdocs` directory, you need first to extract the relevant Trac resources using the `deploy` command of TracAdmin:</ins> </td>
                  </tr><tr>
                          <th> </th><th>101</th><td class="r"><ins>[[TracAdminHelp(deploy)]]</ins> </td>
                  </tr><tr class="last">
                          <th> </th><th>102</th><td class="r"><ins></ins> </td>
                  </tr>
            </tbody><tbody class="unmod">
                  <tr>
                          <th>72</th><th>103</th><td class="l"><span></span> </td>
                  </tr><tr>
                          <th>73</th><th>104</th><td class="l"><span>== Adding Authentication ==</span> </td>
                  </tr>
            </tbody>
              <tbody class="skipped">
                <tr>
                  <th><a href="/wiki/TracCgi?version=1#L113">…</a></th>
                  <th><a href="/wiki/TracCgi?version=2#L144">…</a></th>
                  <td> </td>
                </tr>
              </tbody>
            <tbody class="unmod">
                  <tr>
                          <th>113</th><th>144</th><td class="l"><span>}}}</span> </td>
                  </tr><tr>
                          <th>114</th><th>145</th><td class="l"><span></span> </td>
                  </tr>
            </tbody><tbody class="mod">
                      <tr class="first">
                        <th>115</th><th> </th><td class="l"><span>For better security, it is recommended that you either enable SSL or at least use the “Digest” authentication scheme instead of “Basic”. Please read the [http://httpd.apache.org/docs/2.0/ Apache HTTPD documentation] to find out more.</span> </td>
                      </tr>
                      <tr>
                        <th> </th><th>146</th><td class="r"><span>For better security, it is recommended that you either enable SSL or at least use the “digest” authentication scheme instead of “Basic”. Please read the [http://httpd.apache.org/docs/2.0/ Apache HTTPD documentation] to find out more. For example, on a Debian 4.0r1 (etch) system the relevant section&nbsp; in apache configuration can look like this:</span> </td>
                      </tr><tr>
                        <th> </th><th>147</th><td class="r"><span>{{{</span> </td>
                      </tr><tr>
                        <th> </th><th>148</th><td class="r"><span>&lt;Location "/trac/login"&gt;</span> </td>
                      </tr><tr>
                        <th> </th><th>149</th><td class="r"><span>&nbsp; &nbsp; LoadModule auth_digest_module /usr/lib/apache2/modules/mod_auth_digest.so</span> </td>
                      </tr><tr>
                        <th> </th><th>150</th><td class="r"><span>&nbsp; &nbsp; AuthType Digest</span> </td>
                      </tr><tr>
                        <th> </th><th>151</th><td class="r"><span>&nbsp; &nbsp; AuthName "trac"</span> </td>
                      </tr><tr>
                        <th> </th><th>152</th><td class="r"><span>&nbsp; &nbsp; AuthDigestDomain /trac</span> </td>
                      </tr><tr>
                        <th> </th><th>153</th><td class="r"><span>&nbsp; &nbsp; AuthUserFile /somewhere/trac.htpasswd</span> </td>
                      </tr><tr>
                        <th> </th><th>154</th><td class="r"><span>&nbsp; &nbsp; Require valid-user</span> </td>
                      </tr><tr>
                        <th> </th><th>155</th><td class="r"><span>&lt;/Location&gt;</span> </td>
                      </tr><tr>
                        <th> </th><th>156</th><td class="r"><span>}}}</span> </td>
                      </tr><tr>
                        <th> </th><th>157</th><td class="r"><span>and you'll have to create your .htpasswd file with htdigest instead of htpasswd as follows:</span> </td>
                      </tr><tr>
                        <th> </th><th>158</th><td class="r"><span>{{{</span> </td>
                      </tr><tr>
                        <th> </th><th>159</th><td class="r"><span># htdigest /somewhere/trac.htpasswd trac admin</span> </td>
                      </tr><tr>
                        <th> </th><th>160</th><td class="r"><span>}}}</span> </td>
                      </tr><tr class="last">
                        <th> </th><th>161</th><td class="r"><span>where the "trac" parameter above is the same as !AuthName above&nbsp; ("Realm" in apache-docs). </span> </td>
                      </tr>
            </tbody><tbody class="unmod">
